<h2>Why We Don't Send Alerts</h2>
<p>Most tools designed to monitor risk rely on alerts. A red banner, a push notification, an urgent email. The thinking is that if something might be wrong, you should be interrupted immediately. But this constant state of alert contributes to <b>creator anxiety and fan behavior</b> becoming a source of stress, not a source of connection.</p>

<p>We believe this is a mistake. An alert is a demand. It breaks your attention and pulls you out of your life, forcing you to react on the system's terms, not your own. The <b>emotional labor of creators</b> is already high; adding a stream of notifications only increases it.</p>

<p>Nilea is not an alarm system. It is a <b>calm workspace for creators</b>, a space for quiet reflection.</p>

<p class="pull">Instead of pushing information out, it provides a place for you to come in.</p>

<p>A place to see what's happening in your audience, to notice patterns, and to decide what matters — all on your own schedule. The goal is to restore a sense of agency, not to create another stream of notifications that you have to manage.</p>

<p>We don't send alerts because your attention is the most valuable thing you have. You should be the one to decide where it goes.</p>
